{{Update|date=April 2017}}
The '''United States Chief Technology Officer''' ('''US CTO'''), also formally an Assistant to the President, is in the [[Office of Science and Technology Policy]].<ref>[https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/04/20/aneesh_chopra_us_cto/ Obama taps America's top techie] The Register, 20 April 2009</ref> This position was created within the Office of Science and Technology Policy by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]]. The U.S. CTO helps the President and their team harness the power of data, innovation and technology on behalf of the American People. The team works closely with others both across and outside government on a broad range of work to upgrade government capability including using applied technology to help create jobs, creating paths to improve [[government services]] with [[cost reduction|lower costs]], higher quality and increased transparency, helping upgrade agencies to use [[open data]] and expanding their [[data science]] capabilities, reduce the [[health care costs|costs of health care]] and [[criminal justice]], increase access to broadband, bring technical talent into government for policy and modern operations input, improve community innovation engagement by agencies working on local challenges, and help keep the nation secure. <ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/09/04/18/Weekly-Address-Efficiency-and-Innovation/ "President's Weekly Address Efficiency and Innovation"], April 18, 2009.</ref>
== History == [[Aneesh Chopra]] was named by [[Barack Obama|President Obama]] as the nation's first CTO in April 2009, and confirmed by the Senate on August 7, 2009. Chopra resigned effective February 8, 2012 and was succeeded by [[Todd Park]], formerly the CTO of the department of Health and Human Services. On September 4, 2014 [[Megan Smith]] was named as the CTO.<!-- || Removed, see rowspan above --> {| class=wikitable ! <!-- Image -->colspan=2|Name !! President !! Term || References |- <!-- | [[File:.jpg|75px]] | ''[[]] (Current)'' | rowspan=3|[[Donald Trump]] || 2014-present || <ref name= >{{cite web |url=https:// |title= |author= |publisher=[[]] |date= |accessdate=2017-01-18}}</ref> --> |- | [[File:Aneesh_Chopra_Portrait.jpg|75px]] |[[Aneesh Chopra]] | rowspan="3" |[[Barack Obama]]<!-- || Removed, see rowspan above --> || 2009–2012 ||<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2009/04/18/tech-industry-cheers-as-obama-taps-aneesh-chopra-for-cto/ |title=Tech Industry Cheers as Obama Taps Aneesh Chopra for CTO |author=Schatz, Amy | publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]] | date=2009-04-18 |accessdate=2017-01-18}}</ref><ref>[https://www.senate.gov/pagelayout/legislative/one_item_and_teasers/nom_confc.htm "Nominations confirmed"], "senate.gov", August 7, 2009.</ref><ref name="nytimes012712">{{cite web |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/27/top-technology-official-leaving-the-white-house/ |title=Top Technology Official Leaving the White House |author=Ashely Southall |publisher=New York Times |date=2012-01-27 |accessdate=2012-03-13}}</ref> |- | [[File:Todd_Park.jpeg|75px]] | [[Todd Park]] || 2012–2014 || <ref name=politico>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0312/73848.html |title=At SXSW, Todd Park talks startups |author=Hart, Kim |publisher=Politico |date=2012-03-11 |accessdate=2012-03-13}}</ref> |- | [[File:Megan_Smith_official_portrait.jpg|75px]] |[[Megan Smith]] || 2014-2017 || <ref name="whitehouse">{{cite web |url=https://www.white